{"title":"Producer-Side Experiments Based on Counterfactual Interleaving Designs for Online Recommender Systems","domain":"IR_REC","seeds":[{"problem":"Producer-side A/B tests in recommender systems must merge treatment and control items into a single list per consumer, which typically violates SUTVA and induces confounding via different effective attentions across groups. Existing counterfactual interleaving methods resolve conflicts ad hoc (e.g., random tie-breaking), leading to biased readouts, especially under imbalanced traffic splits.","method":"The paper formalizes producer-side experimentation using an attention function h over ranks and shows observed readouts equal intrinsic utility u composed with a convoluted attention h_k via convolution kernels π_kj induced by the merging rule. It proposes two design principles: (1) Consistency—π_kj must be invariant across treatment k so h_k does not differ by group; (2) Monotonicity—π_kj must be stochastically non-decreasing in j so h_k remains non-increasing. Theorem 4.1 identifies the attention-convolution confounding; with these principles, the expected experiment readouts correctly reflect ranker quality (Corollary 4.4)."},{"problem":"How to construct a valid merged ranker that resolves conflicts between counterfactual rankings R0 and R1 while enabling unbiased producer-side comparisons at any ramp percentage.","method":"Introduce a rigorous counterfactual interleaving procedure: (i) compute control and treatment counterfactual rankings R0 and R1; (ii) form the SUTVA ranker R* by assigning each item its position from its group’s counterfactual; (iii) derive the final merged ranker R by preserving R*’s relative order and resolving ties with a non-constant probability β0(x,y). The tie-break β0(x,y) is derived in closed form (Theorem 5.1) as a function of traffic allocations p0,p1 and whether each conflicting item would rank above j under the opposite model (R1(x), R0(y)), guaranteeing identical position distributions across groups (consistency) and, further, stochastic dominance of kernels with rank (monotonicity; Theorem 5.2). In some cases β0 is 0 or 1, yielding deterministic resolution instead of random tie-breaking."},{"problem":"Deploying producer-side experiments at scale can be computationally heavy when generating both counterfactual rankings across multi-stage pipelines, and prior interleaving led to significant creator misplacement in practice.","method":"Provide a deployment recipe and computational shortcut: when treatment’s candidate generators strictly superset control’s, compute only the treatment counterfactual ranking once, then obtain the control ranking by filtering and filling from the treatment list, avoiding duplicate pipeline passes. In LinkedIn’s online edge recommender, replacing UniCoRn with the proposed design corrected widespread misplacements (≈85% of creators previously off by ±2–3 positions) and yielded fair, interpretable producer-side readouts."}]}
